🧭 Project Overview

In this exercise, we configure and secure SSH authentication using key-based access. SSH (Secure Shell) is the primary protocol used for remote server access in Linux environments.

Instead of using passwords, we implement public key authentication, which is more secure and widely used in DevOps and production systems.

🎯 Objective
Understand SSH authentication mechanisms
Configure key-based authentication
Disable password-based login (optional hardening)
Verify secure remote access
Reinforce secure DevOps access practices
🧰 Environment
Linux server (CentOS / Ubuntu lab environment)
SSH service (sshd)
Client + server setup (jump host + app server)
sudo/root privileges
📌 Concept Explanation

SSH supports two main authentication methods:

1. Password Authentication
username + password
Less secure
Vulnerable to brute-force attacks
2. Key-Based Authentication (Recommended)
Private Key (Client) ↔ Public Key (Server)
Strong cryptographic authentication
No password required
Industry standard for DevOps and cloud systems
🔐 How SSH Key Authentication Works
Client generates key pair
        ↓
Public key copied to server (~/.ssh/authorized_keys)
        ↓
Client connects using private key
        ↓
Server verifies identity without password
🛠️ Implementation Steps
1. Generate SSH key pair (on client / jump host)
ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 4096
🔍 Explanation
-t rsa → RSA encryption algorithm
-b 4096 → strong 4096-bit key
Generates:
Private key: id_rsa
Public key: id_rsa.pub
2. Copy public key to target server
ssh-copy-id user@server-ip
Alternative manual method:
cat ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub

Then paste into:

~/.ssh/authorized_keys

on the target server.

3. Set correct permissions

On the server:

chmod 700 ~/.ssh
chmod 600 ~/.ssh/authorized_keys
🔐 Why this matters:

SSH is strict about permissions:

.ssh directory must be private
authorized_keys must not be publicly writable
4. Test SSH login
ssh user@server-ip

Expected result:

Login occurs without password prompt
5. (Optional Hardening) Disable password authentication

Edit SSH config:

sudo vi /etc/ssh/sshd_config
Update settings:
PasswordAuthentication no
PermitRootLogin no

Restart SSH:

sudo systemctl restart sshd
🔐 Security Insight

Key-based authentication improves security by:

Eliminating password brute-force attacks
Enabling secure automation (CI/CD pipelines)
Supporting cloud-native infrastructure access
Providing stronger cryptographic identity verification
🏗️ Real-World Use Cases
Scenario	Usage
AWS EC2 access	SSH key pairs instead of passwords
CI/CD pipelines	Jenkins/GitHub Actions SSH deployment
Server automation	Ansible remote execution
Kubernetes nodes	Secure cluster communication
Production systems	Password authentication disabled
⚠️ Common Mistakes
❌ Incorrect file permissions on .ssh
❌ Forgetting to restart SSH service
❌ Using weak SSH keys (less than 2048-bit)
❌ Losing private key access
❌ Locking out root user accidentally
📚 Key Takeaways
SSH is the primary remote access tool in DevOps
Key-based authentication is the industry standard
Security depends heavily on correct file permissions
Password authentication should be avoided in production
SSH is foundational for automation and cloud operations
